                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 2126/81.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        Minister <persName type="to">Furniss</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1908-02-07">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 7, 1908</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Mr. Bacon acknowledges telegram of February 5; says note has been taken of the
                    proposal of the other foreign representatives to deport refugees, and directs
                    Mr. Furniss to inform his colleagues that the United States can not join in this
                    proceeding. States that the naval commander reports that it has been suggested
                    to deport all the refugees to Cuba, and advises Mr. Furniss that as that island
                    is now under the responsible administration of the United States, any proposal
                    so to make it a place of political asylum could not be sanctioned. Mr. Bacon
                    instructs him not to lend either official or personal support to any such
                    action.</p>
            </div>
